147. 30. Qualem autem deum intellegere nos possumus &off

“How can we form for ourselves an idea of a god without virtue ?” For intellegere in this signification compl, 10,25; 14, 36; II, 21, 54. The following argumentation is also borrowed from Carneades. See Sext. Emp. lx,152ff. It simply shows however that categories, which apply very well to men and human relations, cannot be transferred to the deity, which Aristotle has shown in regard to the various virtues Eth. Nic. X, 8.
